\title{Efficient Hybrid-action Search with QoR Prediction for Logic Synthesis Sequence Optimization\\
}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Logic synthesis sequence optimization plays a critical role in determining the quality of results (QoRs) of modern digital design flows. Given the highly discrete and combinatorial search space, a variety of automatic searching methods have been proposed. However, most existing methods assume a fixed sequence length, do not explicitly exploit empirically validated macro command patterns, and still rely on frequent exact ABC invocations during search, resulting in high runtime overhead. In this paper, we propose a predictor-enhanced Bayesian optimization framework with a hybrid-action search space. At the core of the framework is an MTL-based predictor that jointly estimates area and delay for a given circuit and synthesis sequence, and is used to support warm-start initialization, candidate pruning, and evaluation skipping during search. The search space combines atomic commands and empirically effective command compositions, and further supports variable-length sequence optimization through \textsc{nop}-based encoding. To improve discrete surrogate modeling, we adopt an LSTM-enhanced SSK kernel that captures both string-level similarity and latent semantic similarity among synthesis sequences. Experiments on 60 circuits from EPFL, OpenABC-D, and VTR benchmarks show that the proposed framework achieves the best ADP on 50 out of 60 benchmarks, reducing the final ADP by 30.4\%, 13.8\%, and 8.5\% on average compared with FlowTune, BOiLS, and LOFMPL, respectively, while delivering more than 15$\times$ speedup on average.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Bayesian optimization, logic synthesis, Multi-task learning.
