\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Logic synthesis is a key stage in modern digital design flows, where the quality of results (QoRs) depends heavily on the synthesis sequence applied to the circuit. Even with the same set of optimization commands, different orderings can lead to substantially different area, delay, and area--delay product (ADP). Therefore, logic synthesis sequence optimization is fundamentally a challenging combinatorial problem over a large discrete search space.

To reduce the reliance on hand-crafted scripts, recent work has increasingly explored automatic sequence optimization using machine learning and black-box search techniques. Representative directions include Bayesian optimization (BO)~\cite{jones1998efficient}, reinforcement learning (RL)~\cite{hosny2020drills,he2023easyso,chowdhury2024abcrl}, bandit-based search~\cite{neto2023flowtune,liu2024cbtune}, and Monte Carlo tree search~\cite{pei2023alphasyn}. BOiLS~\cite{grosnit2022boils} formulates logic synthesis as a BO problem and shows that Gaussian-process-based search can improve sample efficiency. DRiLLS~\cite{hosny2020drills} pioneers the use of deep RL for logic synthesis, while FlowTune~\cite{neto2023flowtune} and CBTune~\cite{liu2024cbtune} cast the problem into bandit-based optimization frameworks. More recently, LOFMPL~\cite{zhu2026lofmpl} improves scalability on larger circuits through MFFC-based partitioning and RL-based exploration. Despite these advances, three key limitations remain. First, most existing methods assume a fixed sequence length, which prevents the search from adapting the optimization depth to different circuits~\cite{hosny2020drills,neto2023flowtune,zhu2026lofmpl}. Second, most methods operate only on atomic commands and do not explicitly exploit empirically effective multi-step command patterns, i.e., macro actions. Third, each sampled candidate still requires an exact ABC invocation for QoR evaluation, which quickly becomes the dominant runtime bottleneck as the search budget or circuit complexity grows.

In this paper, we propose a predictor-enhanced BO framework for logic synthesis sequence search. The framework first represents each design as an AIG-derived directed graph in which complemented edges are converted into explicit NOT nodes and latches are preserved as sequential-boundary nodes, allowing the model to handle both combinational and sequential circuits in a unified way. A graph encoder captures structural information from the circuit, while an LSTM-based sequence encoder models the semantics of synthesis sequences after macro expansion. On top of the resulting joint representation, we design a multi-task predictor for joint area and delay estimation, where cross-task multi-head attention is used to capture the strong coupling between the two QoR objectives. We further integrate this predictor into the BO process through a hybrid action space with atomic actions, macro actions, and \textsc{nop}-based variable-length encoding. In addition, the GP surrogate is enhanced with an LSTM-enhanced subsequence string kernel (SSK)~\cite{lodhi2002text}, while the predictor is used for warm-start initialization, candidate pruning, and evaluation skipping during acquisition-driven search over a discrete candidate pool.

Our experiments are conducted on 60 circuits from the EPFL~\cite{amaru2015epfl}, OpenABC-D~\cite{chowdhury2021openabcd}, and VTR~\cite{murray2020vtr8} benchmark suites. The predictor achieves area/delay $R^2$ values of 0.98/0.99 on combinational circuits and 0.94/0.96 on sequential circuits. Compared with three representative open-source baselines, namely FlowTune~\cite{neto2023flowtune}, BOiLS~\cite{grosnit2022boils}, and LOFMPL~\cite{zhu2026lofmpl}, the proposed framework achieves the best ADP on 50 out of 60 benchmarks, reducing the final ADP by 30.4\%, 13.8\%, and 8.5\%, respectively, while delivering more than 15$\times$ speedup on average.

The contributions of this paper are summarized as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item We propose a predictor-enhanced Bayesian optimization framework for logic synthesis sequence search, which improves both optimization quality and search efficiency.
    
    \item We define a hybrid action space that combines atomic actions and macro actions, and enable variable-length synthesis sequence search through \textsc{nop}-based encoding.
    
    \item We develop a unified multi-task QoR predictor for combinational and sequential circuits based on an AIG-derived graph representation and joint graph--sequence encoding, with cross-task attention to capture the coupling between area and delay.
    
    \item We integrate the predictor into Bayesian optimization via an LSTM-enhanced SSK kernel, warm-start initialization, candidate pruning, and evaluation skipping.
\end{itemize}

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. Section II presents the preliminary background. The proposed multi-task QoR predictor is introduced in Section III. Section IV details the proposed Bayesian optimization framework for synthesis sequence search. Section V provides the experimental results. Finally, Section VI concludes the paper.

