\section{Preliminary}

\subsection{Bayesian Optimization}

% Bayesian Optimization (BO) optimizes black-box functions by constructing a computationally inexpensive surrogate model, making it well-suited for logic synthesis sequence optimization, where high evaluation costs are a major concern.

BO consists of two components: the surrogate model and the acquisition function. The surrogate model $\hat{f}$ approximates the unknown objective function using a set of evaluated samples $\mathcal{D}_t = \{(\mathbf{x}_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^{t}$, where $y_i = f(\mathbf{x}_i)$. It provides a cheap estimate and a measure of confidence for unseen candidate.

The acquisition function $a(\mathbf{x}; \hat{f})$ evaluates candidate points by balancing exploitation and exploration. BO iterates through model fitting, candidate selection, function evaluation, and dataset updating until the evaluation budget is exhausted.

\subsection{Multi-Task Learning}

Multi-task learning (MTL) jointly learns multiple related tasks by exploiting their shared underlying structure \cite{caruana1997multitask,ruder2017overview}. A typical MTL framework consists of a shared backbone, together with task-specific branches and task-interaction mechanisms, so as to capture both shared and task-dependent representations within a unified model.
In QoR prediction, area and delay form a natural multi-task setting: they share the same circuit and synthesis context while focusing on different design properties, making joint learning effective for capturing shared information and task-specific distinctions.

\subsection{Multi-Head Attention}

Multi-head attention (MHA) is a commonly used feature interaction mechanism that enables information exchange through attention-based aggregation \cite{vaswani2017attention}. Given a query matrix $Q$, a key matrix $K$, and a value matrix $V$, attention measures the compatibility between queries and keys, and uses the resulting weights to aggregate the values. The scaled dot-product attention is defined as
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Attention}(Q,K,V)=
\mathrm{softmax}\!\left(\frac{QK^{\top}}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V,
\label{eq:attn}
\end{equation}
where $d_k$ is the dimensionality of the key vectors.

MHA extends this operation by applying multiple attention heads in parallel. For the $h$-th head,
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{head}_{h}=
\mathrm{Attention}(QW_{h}^{Q},KW_{h}^{K},VW_{h}^{V}),
\label{eq:head}
\end{equation}
where $W_h^Q$, $W_h^K$, and $W_h^V$ are learnable projection matrices. The outputs of all heads are then concatenated and linearly projected:
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{MHA}(Q,K,V)=
\mathrm{Concat}(\mathrm{head}_1,\ldots,\mathrm{head}_H)W^{O},
\label{eq:mha}
\end{equation}
where $H$ is the number of heads and $W^O$ is the output projection matrix \cite{vaswani2017attention}. By using multiple heads, MHA can model diverse interaction patterns in different representation subspaces, which is particularly useful for capturing cross-task correlations from multiple perspectives.
In this work, MHA is employed in the feature-sharing module to
facilitate information exchange across task features, which can help the
model capture shared yet task-relevant interactions.






