\section{Multi-Learning-Task-based QoR Predictor}

\subsection{Feature Encoding}

In logic synthesis, circuits are first parsed into and-inverter graphs
(AIGs), which provide a compact structural representation of logic
dependencies. In the original AIG, combinational logic is represented by
AND nodes connected through directed signal edges, where an edge can be
either regular or complemented; for sequential circuits, latches are
also retained in the graph. For learning, we further transform the AIG
into a directed node-edge graph by explicitly converting complemented
edges into NOT nodes and retaining latches as explicit sequential-boundary
nodes. The processed graph contains three node types,
namely AND, NOT, and LATCH, while directed edges represent signal
propagation between nodes.

To support sequential circuits, each LATCH node serves as a boundary
between the upstream and downstream combinational logic, so that message
propagation does not pass through latch outgoing edges. This treatment is consistent with
delay analysis in logic synthesis, where critical paths are evaluated
between sequential boundaries rather than across the entire feedback
structure. Consequently, the sequential circuit is decomposed into a set
of combinational subgraphs, enabling DAG-based logic-level computation.

Each node is associated with the features summarized in
Table~\ref{tab:node_feat}, which are informative for predicting circuit
area and delay. Specifically, node type is encoded as a one-hot vector,
the logic level is computed on the combinational subgraphs obtained
after cutting at LATCH boundaries, and the PI/PO attributes are encoded
as binary indicators attached to the corresponding source or sink nodes in
the processed graph.



