The circuit graph is encoded by a Graph Isomorphism Network
(GIN)~\cite{xu2019powerful}, which iteratively updates each node
representation by aggregating information from its neighbours:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{h}_v^{(\ell+1)}=
\mathrm{MLP}\!\left(
(1+\epsilon^{(\ell)})\mathbf{h}_v^{(\ell)}
+\sum_{u\in\mathcal{N}(v)}\mathbf{h}_u^{(\ell)}
\right),
\label{eq:gin}
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{h}_v^{(\ell)}$ denotes the representation of node $v$ at
layer $\ell$, $\mathcal{N}(v)$ is the neighbourhood of $v$, and
$\epsilon^{(\ell)}$ is a learnable parameter. In this way, each node
embedding captures both its own attributes and the local structural
context of the circuit graph. Global mean pooling is then applied over
all node embeddings to obtain a circuit-level representation
$\mathbf{g}$.

For a synthesis sequence $\mathbf{x}=(x_1,\ldots,x_K)$, the
\emph{ActionEncoder} expands each action into a sequence of ABC atomic
commands, where macro actions are decomposed into multiple
atomic commands. Each atomic command is one-hot encoded over the command vocabulary $\mathcal{C}$, where $|\mathcal{C}|=32$. The resulting command sequence is encoded by an LSTM~\cite{hochreiter1997long} to produce a sequence representation
$\mathbf{e}$.

The final predictor input is formed by concatenating the circuit
representation and the synthesis-sequence representation,
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{z} = [\mathbf{g}\;\|\;\mathbf{e}],
\label{eq:joint_repr}
\end{equation}
which is then fed into the downstream predictor. 


\subsection{Multi-Task-Learning-based QoR Predictor}
\begin{figure*}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{predictor.png}
    \caption{Multi-Task-Learning-based QoR Predictor.}
    \label{fig:predictor}
\end{figure*}
Given the joint representation \(\mathbf{z}\), our MTL-based predictor
simultaneously estimates both area and delay. As shown in
Fig.~\ref{fig:predictor}, the predictor consists of three main
components: task-specific feature extraction, cross-task feature
sharing, and two task-specific prediction heads, each dedicated to one
of the two tasks.

The process is initialized by setting both task features to the joint
representation \(\mathbf{z}\):
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{a}^{(0)}=\mathbf{z}, \qquad
\mathbf{F}_{d}^{(0)}=\mathbf{z}.
\label{eq:init_task_feat}
\end{equation}

The task-specific feature extraction module refines the feature
representation of each task independently. Unless otherwise specified,
different MLP blocks do not share parameters across tasks, layers, or
functional modules. At layer \(j\), the feature
of the area task (\(a\)) is updated by a residual MLP as
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{a}^{(j)}
=
\mathrm{MLP}
\bigl(\mathbf{F}_{a}^{(j)}\bigr)
+\mathbf{F}_{a}^{(j)},
\label{eq:self_a}
\end{equation}
and the delay task (\(d\)) is updated analogously:
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{d}^{(j)}
=
\mathrm{MLP}
\bigl(\mathbf{F}_{d}^{(j)}\bigr)
+\mathbf{F}_{d}^{(j)}.
\label{eq:self_d}
\end{equation}
This module aims to derive task-oriented representations from the shared
input, since area prediction is more related to logic size and
structural complexity, whereas delay prediction is more sensitive to
logic depth and critical-path information. The residual connection helps
preserve the shared information while enhancing the task-specific
characteristics.

The task-specific features are further processed by a cross-task feature
sharing module based on multi-head attention (MHA), where the three
inputs correspond to query, key, and value, respectively. This module is
motivated by the fact that area and delay are physically coupled in
logic synthesis: reducing area may increase delay, while optimizations
for timing often introduce additional logic cost. Therefore, interaction 
patterns learned from one target can provide
auxiliary cues for reweighting the representation of the other. For
the area task (\(a\)), two attention features are computed from the
area and delay branches, respectively:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{A}_{a,1}^{(j)}
=
\mathrm{MHA}\!\left(
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{a}^{(j)},
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{a}^{(j)},
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{a}^{(j)}
\right),
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{A}_{a,2}^{(j)}
=
\mathrm{MHA}\!\left(
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{d}^{(j)},
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{d}^{(j)},
\widetilde{\mathbf{F}}_{a}^{(j)}
\right).
\label{eq:share_a_attn}
\end{equation}
The residual connection on \(\mathbf{A}_{a,1}^{(j)}\) preserves the
dominant task-specific component for area prediction, while
\(\mathbf{A}_{a,2}^{(j)}\) provides auxiliary cross-task information
from the delay branch.
These two attention features are concatenated and
projected to obtain a fused sharing feature:
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{A}}_{a}^{(j)}
=
\mathrm{MLP}
\!\left(
\left[
\mathbf{A}_{a,1}^{(j)}
\;\|\;
\mathbf{A}_{a,2}^{(j)}
\right]
\right)
+
\mathbf{A}_{a,1}^{(j)}.
\label{eq:share_a_fuse}
\end{equation}
The updated area feature is then obtained as
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{a}^{(j+1)}
=
\mathrm{MLP}
\!\left(
\hat{\mathbf{A}}_{a}^{(j)}
\right)
+
\mathbf{F}_{a}^{(j)}.
\label{eq:share_a_update}
\end{equation}
The delay branch follows the same procedure. Through this process, the
predictor preserves task-specific information while allowing each task
to selectively incorporate beneficial signals from the other task.

After the final layer \(L\), the refined task features are fed into two
task-specific MLP heads to produce the area and delay predictions:
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}_{a}
=
\mathrm{MLP}\!\left(\mathbf{F}_{a}^{(L)}\right), 
\hat{y}_{d}
=
\mathrm{MLP}\!\left(\mathbf{F}_{d}^{(L)}\right).
\label{eq:pred_heads}
\end{equation}
The model is trained by jointly minimizing the mean squared errors of
the two regression targets, and the predicted area and delay are further used to enhance Bayesian optimization.

\section{Bayesian Optimization Framework}
Algo.~\ref{alg:main} outlines the proposed BO framework for synthesis sequence search. The optimization target is a scalar QoR objective, which may correspond to delay, area, or ADP.
The algorithm first performs predictor-guided initialization and GP warm-start (Lines~2--8). 
In each iteration, it fits the GP surrogate (Line~11), generates candidate sequences and prunes clearly poor ones using the auxiliary predictor (Lines~13--14), and then computes acquisition scores to select a diverse batch (Lines~16--18). 
Before exact ABC evaluation, the selected candidates are further filtered by a joint GP--predictor screening criterion, so that only promising candidates are evaluated exactly (Lines~20--25). 
The incumbent sequence and optimization state are subsequently updated (Lines~27--30). 
The key components of this framework are detailed in the following subsections.
\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{BO for Synthesis Sequence Search}
\label{alg:main}
\textbf{Input:} Circuit $C$, action alphabet $\mathcal{A}$, auxiliary predictor $\mathcal{P}$, evaluation budget $T$, initial sample size $n_0$, batch size $q$ \\
\textbf{Output:} Best sequence $\mathbf{x}^{+}$
\begin{algorithmic}[1]

\STATE \texttt{// Initialization}
\STATE $\mathcal{U}_0 \gets \textsc{BuildInitialPool}(\mathcal{A} \cup \{\textsc{nop}\}, 5n_0)$
\STATE $\mathcal{X}_0 \gets \textsc{SelectTopByPredictor}(\mathcal{U}_0, \mathcal{P}, n_0)$
\STATE $\mathcal{D} \gets \textsc{ExactEvaluateSet}(C, \mathcal{X}_0)$
\STATE $\tilde{\mathcal{D}} \gets \textsc{GeneratePseudoObservations}(\mathcal{P})$
\STATE $\mathbf{x}^{+} \gets \textsc{GetBestSequence}(\mathcal{D})$
\STATE $\mathcal{E} \gets \textsc{BuildElitePool}(\mathcal{D})$
\STATE $\mathcal{T} \gets \textsc{InitializeTrustRegion}(\mathbf{x}^{+})$

\WHILE{$|\mathcal{D}| < T$}

    \STATE \texttt{// Gaussian process fitting}
    \STATE $\theta \gets \textsc{FitGaussianProcess}(\mathcal{D} \cup \tilde{\mathcal{D}}, k_{\mathrm{CC\mbox{-}SSK}})$

    \STATE \texttt{// Candidate generation and pruning}
    \STATE $\mathcal{C} \gets \textsc{GenerateCandidatePool}(\mathcal{T}, \mathcal{E}, \mathcal{A} \cup \{\textsc{nop}\})$
    \STATE $\mathcal{C} \gets \textsc{PruneCandidatesByPredictor}(\mathcal{C}, \mathcal{P})$

    \STATE \texttt{// Scoring and batch selection}
    \STATE $(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\sigma}^2) \gets \textsc{PredictPosterior}(\theta, \mathcal{C})$
    \STATE $\mathbf{s} \gets \textsc{ComputeAcquisitionScores}(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\sigma}^2)$
    \STATE $\mathcal{B} \gets \textsc{SelectDiverseBatch}(\mathcal{C}, \mathbf{s}, q)$

    \STATE \texttt{// Exact evaluation and update}
    \FORALL{$\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{B}$}
        \IF{$\textsc{ShouldSkipEvaluation}(\mathbf{x}, \theta, \mathcal{P}, \mathbf{x}^{+})$}
            \STATE \textbf{continue}
        \ENDIF
        \STATE $y \gets \textsc{ExactEvaluateQoR}(C, \mathbf{x})$
        \STATE $\mathcal{D} \gets \mathcal{D} \cup \{(\mathbf{x}, -y)\}$
    \ENDFOR

    \STATE $\mathbf{x}^{+} \gets \textsc{GetBestSequence}(\mathcal{D})$
    \STATE $\mathcal{E} \gets \textsc{BuildElitePool}(\mathcal{D})$
    \STATE $\mathcal{T} \gets \textsc{UpdateTrustRegion}(\mathcal{T}, \mathcal{D}, \mathbf{x}^{+})$
    \STATE $\theta \gets \textsc{UpdateGPHyperparameters}(\theta, \mathcal{D})$

\ENDWHILE
\small
\RETURN $\mathbf{x}^{+}$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}


\subsection{Search Space}

In this paper, we refer to the set of logic optimization commands as the \emph{action space}. 
Specifically, the action space consists of 32 \textit{\textbf{atomic actions}}, as listed in Table~\ref{tab:allactions}. 
To further improve the quality and efficiency of sequence search, we additionally define 15 multi-step command combinations, referred to as \emph{\textbf{macro actions}}, as shown in Table~\ref{tab:macros}. Macro actions compress frequently effective multi-step patterns into single decision variables and improve the diversity of the initial candidate pool. Therefore, the set of executable synthesis actions $\mathcal{A}$ is defined as Eq.~\eqref{eq:actions}, where $\mathcal{A}_{\mathrm{atom}}$ and $\mathcal{A}_{\mathrm{mac}}$ denote the sets of atomic actions and macro actions:
\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{A} = \mathcal{A}_{\mathrm{atom}} \cup \mathcal{A}_{\mathrm{mac}}.
  \label{eq:actions}
\end{equation} 

Conventional sequence search frameworks usually require the length of the target synthesis sequence to be fixed in advance. 
However, due to the complexity of logic synthesis and the associated runtime overhead, longer command sequences do not necessarily lead to better QoR. 
Therefore, it is desirable to support variable-length sequence search. 
To achieve this without modifying the structure of a fixed-length search framework, we further introduce an additional dummy command, denoted by \textsc{nop}, in the sequence representation. 
Before exact execution, all \textsc{nop} are removed from the generated sequence, allowing a fixed-length representation to encode variable-length effective synthesis sequences. Thus, a synthesis sequence can be represented as a fixed-length tuple with $\mathcal{A}$ and $\textsc{nop}$:
\begin{equation}
  \mathbf{x} = (x_1,\ldots,x_K) \in (\mathcal{A} \cup \{\textsc{nop}\})^K,
  \label{eq:sequence}
\end{equation}
where $K$ denotes the maximum sequence length.
