\section{Experimental Results}

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

The experiments are conducted on 60 circuits drawn from EPFL, openABC-D, and VTR benchmarks. We compare the proposed framework with three representative open-source sequence-search frameworks, including LOFMPL, BOiLS, and FlowTune. All experiments are performed on a server equipped with an Intel(R) Xeon(R) Gold 6148 CPU @ 2.40\,GHz, an NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4090 GPU, and 500\,GB of memory. For logic synthesis and technology mapping, the ASAP 7\,nm library is adopted as the target technology library.

To ensure a fair comparison, all search frameworks are evaluated under the same computational budget. Specifically, the maximum number of search iterations is set to 200, and the runtime is limited to 100{,}000 seconds for each benchmark. If a framework exceeds the time limit, the best result obtained before timeout is reported as the final result.


\subsection{Predictor Evaluation}

The predictor is evaluated on 112 circuits collected from three public
benchmark sources, namely VTR~8~\cite{murray2020vtr8},
OpenABC-D~\cite{chowdhury2021openabcd}, and the EPFL benchmark
suite~\cite{amaru2015epfl}. These circuits include both purely
combinational and sequential designs, and span a wide range of logic
depths and circuit sizes.For all experiments, the dataset is \textbf{split at
the circuit level} into training, validation, and test sets with a ratio
of 6:3:1, such that each circuit appears in only one split. For each circuit, we generate
200 purely random synthesis sequences from the search space defined in
Table.~\ref{tab:macros}. These sequences differ in length, composition, and ordering.



We evaluate the predictor using the coefficient of determination
($R^2$) and the mean absolute percentage error (MAPE):
\begin{equation}
R^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2}
{\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i-\bar{y})^2},
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{MAPE} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}
\left|\frac{y_i-\hat{y}_i}{y_i}\right|\times 100\%.
\end{equation}
A larger $R^2$ indicates that the predictions better match the
ground-truth values, while a smaller MAPE indicates lower relative
prediction error. 

In all experiments, we use a two-layer GIN with hidden dimension 128
and global mean pooling for circuit encoding, and an LSTM with hidden
size 128 for synthesis-sequence encoding, where each atomic command is
represented as a 32-dimensional one-hot vector. The multi-task
predictor contains two task-interaction layers with hidden dimension
128, and the cross-task attention module uses 4 heads. The model is
trained with Adam at a learning rate of 0.001. Both area and delay are
log-transformed before training, and the overall loss is defined as the
sum of the two task losses.

