To further understand the contribution of each component, we conduct ablation experiments by removing the neural predictor, the LSTM-based sequence encoder, and the macro-action space, respectively. Table~\ref{tab:ablation} reports the averaged results in terms of area, delay, normalized ADP respected to the full model, the number of ABC calls, and runtime.

First, removing the predictor leads to a substantial increase in search cost. Without the predictor, the average number of ABC calls rises from 124 to 200, resulting in a 3.53$\times$ longer runtime. Although the variant without the predictor attains a slightly lower ADP, this gain is obtained at the cost of exhausting the full evaluation budget. This result indicates that the neural predictor primarily serves as an efficiency-oriented module, as it effectively filters low-value candidates and reduces expensive ABC evaluations while preserving competitive final QoR.

Second, removing macro actions results in the largest degradation in normalized ADP, which increases to 1.12. This result suggests that macro actions improve search quality because they encode empirically validated multi-command optimization patterns and explicitly seed the search with stronger initial sequences, thereby guiding the exploration toward higher-quality regions of the search space.

Third, removing the LSTM-based sequence encoder leads to a moderate increase in normalized ADP to 1.03. In this case, both area and delay become slightly worse. This observation suggests that the LSTM encoder improves the quality of sequence representation used in surrogate-assisted search, thereby helping the ADP-driven optimization process identify solutions with a better overall area--delay balance.

In general, the ablation results show that the three components contribute in different ways. The neural predictor mainly improves search efficiency by reducing the number of expensive oracle calls, whereas the LSTM encoder and macro actions improve the final ADP achieved by the search framework.

